                {
                    "id" : "prerequisites",
                    "text" : [ "<p><span id=\"htZoomImageMsg\"></span></p>",
                                "<p class=\"topdesc\"><i>The abbreviations A.E.C, B.C.E (Before Common Era), and negative years serve as generalizations for representing eras preceding the initial days of the calendars.</i></p>",
                                { "text" : "### Prerequisites\n\nWe recommend reading the first part of this study on the cradles of civilization before proceeding with this text",
                                 "source" : [ { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "893e651f-8354-4d9a-b182-893512a3bbbe",
                                                "text": "<i>History Tracers Editors. Berços Civilizatórios (Parte I)</i>",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2024", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }} ],
                                  "isTable" : false,
                                  "format" : "markdown"
                               },
                               "<p>In this text, we will focus on the remaining three cradles of civilization: Egypt, the Indus Valley, and China.</p>",
                                "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"imgMWPWEEC\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgMWPWEEC', '0%')\" src=\"images/mapswire/mapswire-world-political-white-equal_earth_cradle.png\" class=\"imgcenterlarge\"/>Figure 1: Cradle of Civilization. © Mapswire (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('dd4f3c8a-6624-4df5-93ac-37e0a4be9fdc'); return false;\"><i>Mapswire</i></a>). Compartilhado sob a licença <a href=\"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0/\" target=\"_blank\">Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International (CC BY-NC-SA 4.0)</p>"
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id" : "egypt",
                    "text" : [ 
                                { "text" : "### Predynastic Egypt\n\nWe are in <htdate0>, but our species is at least 250,000 years old. For millennia, humans lived in Africa, the continent where one of the world’s oldest civilizations, Egypt, emerged. Although Egypt is best known for its dynastic period and the iconic pyramids, communities had already been established there thousands of years earlier, domesticating animals and plants",
                                 "source" : [ { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "2be849f1-551b-44eb-8fc6-87027dbf8a68",
                                                "text": "Mounier, A., & Mirazón Lahr, M.",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2019", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "1fac1f5e-4274-43f9-a8cf-01ca1c3b1450",
                                                "text": "Linseele V, Van Neer W, Thys S, Phillipps R, Cappers R, Wendrich W, <i>et al</i>.",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2014", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }}
                                 ],
                                 "isTable" : false,
                                 "fill_dates" : [
                                    {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "now", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }
                                 ],
                                 "format" : "markdown"
                               },
                               "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"imgMWPWEEJ\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgMWPWEEJ', '0%')\" src=\"images/mapswire/mapswire-continent_af-physical-map-africa-lambert-az-hemi-265_egypt_001.jpg\" class=\"imgcenter\"/>Figure 2: Human migration. © Mapswire (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('dd4f3c8a-6624-4df5-93ac-37e0a4be9fdc'); return false;\"><i>Mapswire</i></a>). Compartido sob licencia <a href=\"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0/\" target=\"_blank\">Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International (CC BY-NC-SA 4.0)</p>",
                               { "text" : "#### The Dynamic Earth\n\nIn the <i>History Tracers</i> atlas, we explored articles showing that continents are not static but shift over time. However, these are not the only transformations our planet has undergone. For example, northern Africa, now dominated by desert, was once a much more humid region",
                                 "source" : [ { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "412e4ddc-54ac-453f-9014-4affa2e96b83",
                                                "text": "History Tracers Editors",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2024", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "59c0b962-d032-4b6c-9498-2341e089510b",
                                                "text": "Allmon, D. W. et al",
                                                "date": { "type": "gregory", "year": "2024", "month": "10", "day": "28" } },
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "750e84b5-9330-4f99-92b0-72469a6a64f4",
                                                "text": "Allmon, D. W. et al" },
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "1fac1f5e-4274-43f9-a8cf-01ca1c3b1450",
                                                "text": "Linseele V, Van Neer W, Thys S, Phillipps R, Cappers R, Wendrich W, <i>et al</i>., pp. 2, 13",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2014", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }}
                                 ],
                                 "isTable" : false,
                                 "format" : "markdown"
                               },
                               { "text" : "#### Faiyum\n\nFaiyum is one of the oldest archaeological sites in Egypt. Evidence of domesticated animals dating back to around <htdate0> has been uncovered there. The discovery of domestic animal bones alongside baskets, like the one shown in Figure 3, suggests that the inhabitants used these baskets for storage and transportation, indicating a sedentary and organized way of life",
                                 "source" : [ { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "5b00d8de-5d74-4516-8c90-aab6a5395b44",
                                                "text": "Cy, 03:18",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2024", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "15f68de8-4571-4f5f-b7db-85c30fa8b616",
                                                "text": "Köhler E. Christiana, pp. 18",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2011", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "3464d1ee-c40a-4bdc-8876-46d5e611b13a",
                                                "text": "Mark, J. J.",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2016", "month" : "1", "day" : "18" }},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "5f232e60-6d02-4d20-9ddf-1b19d372fcab",
                                                "text": "Doman, Peter F., <i>et al</i>"},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "1fac1f5e-4274-43f9-a8cf-01ca1c3b1450",
                                                "text": "Linseele V, Van Neer W, Thys S, Phillipps R, Cappers R, Wendrich W, <i>et al</i>., pp. 6 - 13",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2014", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }}
                                 ],
                                 "fill_dates" : [
                                    {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "-5400", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }
                                 ],
                                 "isTable" : false,
                                 "format" : "markdown"
                               },
                               "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"imgMid001\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgMid001', '0%')\" src=\"images/BritshMuseum/mid_00108766_001.jpg\" class=\"imgcenter\"/>Figure 3: Oblong basket of woven reed. © Trustees of the British Museum (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillPrimarySource('07e20bf5-f3b4-4093-8a92-ab6933be279a'); return false;\"><i>The British Museum</i></a>). Shared under a <a href=\"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0/\" target=\"_blank\">Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International (CC BY-NC-SA 4.0)</a>.</p>",
                               { "text" : "#### Merimde\n\nAlthough the Merimde site cannot be precisely dated, it is estimated that its occupation occurred between <htdate0> and <htdate1>. Archaeological findings indicate a well-established society where agriculture played a central role",
                                 "source" : [ { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "5b00d8de-5d74-4516-8c90-aab6a5395b44",
                                                "text": "Cy, 09:03",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2024", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "15f68de8-4571-4f5f-b7db-85c30fa8b616",
                                                "text": "Köhler E. Christiana, pp. 18",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2011", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "1fac1f5e-4274-43f9-a8cf-01ca1c3b1450",
                                                "text": "Linseele V, Van Neer W, Thys S, Phillipps R, Cappers R, Wendrich W, <i>et al</i>., pp. 6 - 13",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2014", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }}
                                 ],
                                 "fill_dates" : [
                                    {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "-4900", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" },
                                    {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "-4700", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }
                                 ],
                                 "isTable" : false,
                                 "format" : "markdown"
                               },
                               { "text" : "#### El Omari\n\nSimilar to the inhabitants of Merimde, the people of El Omari hunted hippopotamuses, possibly to protect their crops. This culture is notable for the development of tools such as knives and blades",
                                 "source" : [ { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "5b00d8de-5d74-4516-8c90-aab6a5395b44",
                                                "text": "Cy, 10:49",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2024", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "15f68de8-4571-4f5f-b7db-85c30fa8b616",
                                                "text": "Köhler E. Christiana, pp. 18 - 19",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2011", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "3464d1ee-c40a-4bdc-8876-46d5e611b13a",
                                                "text": "Mark, J. J.",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2016", "month" : "1", "day" : "18" }},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "1fac1f5e-4274-43f9-a8cf-01ca1c3b1450",
                                                "text": "Linseele V, Van Neer W, Thys S, Phillipps R, Cappers R, Wendrich W, <i>et al</i>., pp. 16",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2014", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }}
                                 ],
                                 "isTable" : false,
                                 "format" : "markdown"
                               },
                               { "text" : "#### Badari\n\nThe Badarian culture, located in Upper Egypt, flourished between <htdate0> and <htdate1>. It is characterized by communities living in portable tents. Evidence suggests that, in addition to seasonal fishing, this culture buried their dead in cemeteries. In Figure 2, the site of Maghar Dendera represents this culture",
                                 "source" : [ { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "5b00d8de-5d74-4516-8c90-aab6a5395b44",
                                                "text": "Cy, 10:49",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2024", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "15f68de8-4571-4f5f-b7db-85c30fa8b616",
                                                "text": "Köhler E. Christiana, pp. 19 - 20",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2011", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "1d5e3549-3ba7-4d74-8a0b-85e3917bdc30",
                                                "text": "The Editors of Encylopedia Britannica"},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "3464d1ee-c40a-4bdc-8876-46d5e611b13a",
                                                "text": "Mark, J. J.",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2016", "month" : "1", "day" : "18" }},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "1fac1f5e-4274-43f9-a8cf-01ca1c3b1450",
                                                "text": "Linseele V, Van Neer W, Thys S, Phillipps R, Cappers R, Wendrich W, <i>et al</i>., pp. 16",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2014", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }}
                                 ],
                                 "fill_dates" : [
                                    {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "-4500", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" },
                                    {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "-4000", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }
                                 ],
                                 "isTable" : false,
                                 "format" : "markdown"
                               },
                               { "text" : "#### Naqada\n\nThe Naqada period (<htdate0> - <htdate1>) is marked by the emergence of characteristics associated with ancient Egypt. Evidence shows that trade networks extended as far as modern-day Iran, and the practice of mummification began during this period. Early hieroglyphs, dating to around <hdate2> and <htdate3>, also appeared, though no complete texts have yet been found",
                                 "source" : [ { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "5b00d8de-5d74-4516-8c90-aab6a5395b44",
                                                "text": "Cy, 10:49",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2024", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "3464d1ee-c40a-4bdc-8876-46d5e611b13a",
                                                "text": "Mark, J. J.",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2016", "month" : "1", "day" : "18" }},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "1fac1f5e-4274-43f9-a8cf-01ca1c3b1450",
                                                "text": "Linseele V, Van Neer W, Thys S, Phillipps R, Cappers R, Wendrich W, <i>et al</i>., pp. 16",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2014", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }}
                                 ],
                                 "fill_dates" : [
                                    {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "-3800", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" },
                                    {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "-2686", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" },
                                    {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "-3400", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" },
                                    {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "-3200", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }
                                 ],
                                 "isTable" : false,
                                 "format" : "markdown"
                               },
                               { "text" : "#### Next steps\n\nIn this section, we explored some of the main cultures and archaeological sites of predynastic Egypt. To delve deeper into the topic, we recommend reviewing the papers and videos used as sources for this study.",
                                 "source" : null,
                                 "isTable" : false,
                                 "format" : "markdown"
                               }
                         ]
                },
                {
                    "id" : "indus_valley",
                    "text" : [ { "text" : "### Indus Valley Civilization\n\nFigure 1 illustrates the Indus Valley Civilization, which spanned the regions that today comprise India and Pakistan. These areas remained united until the promulgation of the India Independence Act on <htdate0>. This civilization derives its name from the Indus River, located in present-day Pakistan. However, its influence extended beyond these borders, with contemporaneous archaeological sites also discovered in Nepal and Afghanistan",
                                 "source" : [ { "type": 0,
                                                "uuid": "e4d3ebbb-5693-4a66-b9bb-5e08afc77e17",
                                                "text": "<i>UK Paralament</i>",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "1947", "month" : "7", "day" : "18" }},
                                              { "type": 0,
                                                "uuid": "8ffbbcdc-27d9-42bb-b9fa-0084df24be5c",
                                                "text": "<i>UK Public General Acts</i>",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "1947", "month" : "7", "day" : "18" }},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "bab5560b-8092-4cd1-9b31-415e0381a946",
                                                "text": "Mark, J. J.",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2020", "month" : "10", "day" : "7" }},
                                              { "type": 0,
                                                "uuid": "b2f2b9dc-e8d0-4589-8b36-529ea7f24e09",
                                                "text": "Abdul Karim Khan, 05:10",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2013", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }},
                                              { "type": 0,
                                                "uuid": "04e14d94-3088-4daa-ab96-9e4b2b8d7c1d",
                                                "text": "Madella, M., & Fuller, D. Q., pp. 1284",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2006", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }}
                                 ],
                                 "isTable" : false,
                                 "fill_dates" : [
                                    {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "1947", "month" : "7", "day" : "18" }
                                 ],
                                 "format" : "markdown"
                               },
                               { "text" : "#### Development\n\nThe available evidence suggests that agriculture in this region between <htdate0> and <hdate1>, though the earliest stages of settlement may still remain undiscovered. The consolidation of these communities occurred between <htdate2> and <htdate3>. From this period onward, the civilization experienced steady advancements in urban planning, ideology, and social organization",
                                 "source" : [ 
                                              { "type": 0,
                                                "uuid": "b2f2b9dc-e8d0-4589-8b36-529ea7f24e09",
                                                "text": "Abdul Karim Khan, 15:29",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2013", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "bab5560b-8092-4cd1-9b31-415e0381a946",
                                                "text": "Mark, J. J.",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2020", "month" : "10", "day" : "7" }},
                                              { "type": 0,
                                                "uuid": "04e14d94-3088-4daa-ab96-9e4b2b8d7c1d",
                                                "text": "Madella, M., & Fuller, D. Q., pp. 1284 - 1285",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2006", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }}
                                 ],
                                 "isTable" : false,
                                 "fill_dates" : [
                                    {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "-7000", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" },
                                    {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "-4300", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" },
                                    {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "-4300", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" },
                                    {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "-3200", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }
                                 ],
                                 "format" : "markdown"
                               },
                               { "text" : "#### Society\n\nAlthough Harappa developed a writing system, as shown in Figure 4, it has not yet been deciphered, limiting our understanding of certain aspects of this society. However, archaeological evidence reveals that urban centers, such as Harappa, were meticulously planned and constructed using standardized bricks. One particularly noteworthy feature of their urban planning is their advanced sanitation system, evidenced by private bathrooms in houses connected to an underground sewage network",
                                 "source" : [ 
                                              { "type": 0,
                                                "uuid": "b2f2b9dc-e8d0-4589-8b36-529ea7f24e09",
                                                "text": "Abdul Karim Khan, 18:29",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2013", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "89b0df4e-5e0f-4343-9912-07bc95ea3d7c",
                                                "text": "Violatti, C.",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2015", "month" : "7", "day" : "5" }},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "bab5560b-8092-4cd1-9b31-415e0381a946",
                                                "text": "Mark, J. J.",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2020", "month" : "10", "day" : "7" }}
                                 ],
                                 "isTable" : false,
                                 "format" : "markdown"
                               },
                               "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"imgHarappaW\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgHarappaW', '0%')\" src=\"images/Ashmolean/28932.jpg\" class=\"imgcenter\"/>Figure 4: Harappa seal. © Ashmolean Museum, University of Oxford (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillPrimarySource('1696d647-d450-44e3-9067-18aac69bce3d'); return false;\">Ashmolean Museum Oxford</a>). Shared under a <a href=\"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0/\" target=\"_blank\">Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International (CC BY-NC-SA 4.0)</a>.</p>",
                               { "text" : "#### Decline\n\nThe exact reasons for the decline of this civilization remain unclear. Hypotheses include natural factors, such as changes in the river's course, and external invasions. However, researchers have yet to reach a consensus on the precise causes",
                                 "source" : [ 
                                              { "type": 0,
                                                "uuid": "b2f2b9dc-e8d0-4589-8b36-529ea7f24e09",
                                                "text": "Abdul Karim Khan, 01:10:20",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2013", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "bab5560b-8092-4cd1-9b31-415e0381a946",
                                                "text": "Mark, J. J.",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2020", "month" : "10", "day" : "7" }},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "1a679cc3-8238-4ece-9035-93993f0827f7",
                                                "text": "Giosan, L. <i>et al</i>",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2012", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }},
                                              { "type": 0,
                                                "uuid": "04e14d94-3088-4daa-ab96-9e4b2b8d7c1d",
                                                "text": "Madella, M., & Fuller, D. Q., pp. 1285 - 1298",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2006", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }}
                                 ],
                                 "isTable" : false,
                                 "format" : "markdown"
                               }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id" : "chinese",
                    "text" : [ { "text" : "### Chinese Civilization\n\nWhen discussing the beginnings of Chinese civilization, it is crucial to distinguish between historical events and those considered legendary.",
                                 "source" : null,
                                 "isTable" : false,
                                 "fill_dates" : null,
                                 "format" : "markdown"
                               },
                               { "text" : "#### Initial Facts\n\nGeographic isolation played a fundamental role in shaping Chinese civilization. This isolation was facilitated by natural barriers such as the Himalayas and southern forests, the East China Sea to the east, and the Gobi Desert to the north. Like the Indus Valley civilization, Chinese civilization developed around a major river—the Yellow River",
                                 "source" : [ { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "cf5ef4bb-268a-4885-98ee-6a9af3c221d3",
                                                "text": "Abdul Karim Khan, 03:56",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2013", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }}
                                 ],
                                 "isTable" : false,
                                 "fill_dates" : [
                                    {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "1947", "month" : "7", "day" : "18" }
                                 ],
                                 "format" : "markdown"
                               },
                               { "text" : "#### The First Dynasty\n\nWhen addressing the first dynasty, it is necessary to differentiate between tradition and archaeological evidence. According to tradition, the Xia Dynasty was the first, beginning with Emperor Yu, who is credited with controlling the Yellow River's floods. The Xia Dynasty is believed to have existed between <htdate0> and <htdate1>. However, its existence remains debated, as the available evidence is indirect and there is no consensus among scholars",
                                 "source" : [ { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "cf5ef4bb-268a-4885-98ee-6a9af3c221d3",
                                                "text": "Abdul Karim Khan, 42:22",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2013", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "d49fa3da-118d-4f4d-bc29-60be879a857c",
                                                "text": "The Editors of Encylopedia Britannica"},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "4494bc0f-6ce0-49dc-9c6b-c2c5dbea56f7",
                                                "text": "Mark, E.",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2016", "month" : "1", "day" : "10" }}
                                 ],
                                 "isTable" : false,
                                 "fill_dates" : [
                                    {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "-2070", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" },
                                    {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "-1600", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }
                                 ],
                                 "format" : "markdown"
                               },
                               { "text" : "In this context, the documented history of China typically begins with the Shang Dynasty, which ruled from approximately <htdate0> and <htdate1>, with its fall occurring between <htdate2> and <htdate3>. The Shang Dynasty emerged during the late Bronze Age. The earliest concrete evidence of their existence includes inscriptions on oracle bones, as shown in Figure 5",
                                 "source" : [ { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "cf5ef4bb-268a-4885-98ee-6a9af3c221d3",
                                                "text": "Abdul Karim Khan, 42:22",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2013", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "d49fa3da-118d-4f4d-bc29-60be879a857c",
                                                "text": "The Editors of Encylopedia Britannica"},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "4494bc0f-6ce0-49dc-9c6b-c2c5dbea56f7",
                                                "text": "Mark, E.",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2016", "month" : "1", "day" : "10" }},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "2fe34b9b-e1a3-4ade-ad5c-4f090fd015e1",
                                                "text": "Menzies, James M., pp. 549 - 551",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "1931", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }}
                                 ],
                                 "isTable" : false,
                                 "fill_dates" : [
                                    {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "-1766", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" },
                                    {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "-1520", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" },
                                    {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "-1122", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" },
                                    {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "-1046", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }
                                 ],
                                 "format" : "markdown"
                               },
                               "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"imgChinese\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgChinese', '0%')\" src=\"images/BritshMuseum/mid_RRC5932_14.jpg\" class=\"imgcenter\"/>Figure 5:Arrowhead made from bone, featuring inscriptions. © Trustees of the British Museum (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('874a8d48-a892-4ad3-8bc4-b34190bd4eba'); return false;\"><i>The British Museum</i></a> ).</p>",
                               { "text" : "During the Shang Dynasty, kings frequently relocated their capitals. Their governmental structure included regional governors and a well-defined nobility. They also developed a 360-day calendar divided into 12 months of 30 days each. Additionally, it was during this time that the Chinese writing system emerged. According to James M. Menzies, there is no evidence linking the Chinese writing system to the Sumerian script, which was developed over a millennium earlier",
                                 "source" : [ { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "cf5ef4bb-268a-4885-98ee-6a9af3c221d3",
                                                "text": "Abdul Karim Khan, 53:18",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2013", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "acbe09fb-994a-4ac0-9a6c-9b8111f74a2b",
                                                "text": "The Editors of Encylopedia Britannica"},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "c828491d-4549-4b52-8648-157bc8607f50",
                                                "text": "Mark, E.",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2016", "month" : "1", "day" : "28" }},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "2fe34b9b-e1a3-4ade-ad5c-4f090fd015e1",
                                                "text": "Menzies, James M., pp. 551 - 553",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "1931", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }}
                                 ],
                                 "isTable" : false,
                                 "format" : "markdown"
                               },
                               { "text" : "Another notable aspect of this period was the extensive use of jade, which was crafted into both objects and weapons",
                                 "source" : [ { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "acbe09fb-994a-4ac0-9a6c-9b8111f74a2b",
                                                "text": "The Editors of Encylopedia Britannica"},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "c828491d-4549-4b52-8648-157bc8607f50",
                                                "text": "Mark, E.",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2016", "month" : "1", "day" : "28" }},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "2fe34b9b-e1a3-4ade-ad5c-4f090fd015e1",
                                                "text": "Menzies, James M., pp. 557 - 558",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "1931", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }}
                                 ],
                                 "isTable" : false,
                                 "format" : "markdown"
                               },
                               { "text" : "#### Decline\n\nThe Shang Dynasty experienced a decline before the foundation of Anyang around <htdate0>. However, its definitive fall occurred in <htdate1> when it was replaced by the Zhou Dynasty",
                                 "source" : [ { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "c828491d-4549-4b52-8648-157bc8607f50",
                                                "text": "Mark, E.",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2016", "month" : "1", "day" : "28" }}
                                 ],
                                 "fill_dates" : [
                                    {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "-1300", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" },
                                    {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "-1046", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }
                                 ],
                                 "isTable" : false,
                                 "format" : "markdown"
                               },
                               "<h3>Conclusion</h3><p>In previous texts and this one, we have explored the six major cradles of civilization. However, this topic is far from exhausted. In upcoming chapters and in the Genealogy section of <i>History Tracers</i> (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('8abed0b5-2e6f-49b4-85bf-c62aad3bbcd1'); return false;\"><i>History Tracers Team</i></a>), we will delve deeper into each of them.</p>",
                                "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\">?</div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: About the Cradles of Civilization</b><br /><br />Identifying these six regions as the starting points of major civilizations does not mean the rest of the world lacked human activity. These regions are highlighted because, over time, their histories and beliefs significantly influenced other peoples.<br /><br />Did you know about these cradles of civilization before studying this material?\"</div></div></center></p>",
                               "<p>Based on our exploration so far, we can use mathematics—the language of nature—to represent this concept more simply. Each cradle of civilization can be depicted as a circle, labeled with a corresponding letter (A - Andes, M - Mesopotamia, O - Mesoamerica, E - Egypt, I - Indus Valley, C - China). These individual circles are then placed within a larger circle (h), symbolizing humanity beyond these regions. Finally, all these circles can merge into a single, unified circle (H), representing humanity as a whole:</p>",
                               "<p class=\"desc\"><svg fill=\"none\" stroke=\"black\"><circle cx=\"145\" cy=\"75\" r=\"70\"></circle> <text x=\"140\" y=\"80\" font-size=\"2em\">h</text> <circle cx=\"110\" cy=\"50\" r=\"10\"></circle>  <text x=\"105\" y=\"55\" font-size=\"1.4em\">A</text> <circle cx=\"148\" cy=\"30\" r=\"10\"></circle>  <text x=\"142\" y=\"35\" font-size=\"1.4em\">M</text>  <circle cx=\"185\" cy=\"50\" r=\"10\"></circle>  <text x=\"180\" y=\"55\" font-size=\"1.4em\">O</text> <circle cx=\"110\" cy=\"90\" r=\"10\"></circle>  <text x=\"105\" y=\"95\" font-size=\"1.4em\">E</text> <circle cx=\"148\" cy=\"120\" r=\"10\"></circle>  <text x=\"146\" y=\"125\" font-size=\"1.4em\">I</text>  <circle cx=\"185\" cy=\"90\" r=\"10\"></circle>  <text x=\"180\" y=\"95\" font-size=\"1.4em\">C</text> </svg></p>",
                                "<p class=\"desc\">Figure 6: Representation of cradle of civilization inside a circle that has all Human beings outside the cradles.</p>",
                        "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\" style=\"background-color: #D7FFE4;\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\" style=\"background-color: #D7FFE4;\"> <i class=\"fa-solid fa-infinity\" style=\"font-size: 1em;\" style=\"font-size: 1em;\"></i><i class=\"fa-solid fa-dna\" style=\"font-size: 1em;\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\" style=\"background-color: #D7FFE4;\"><b>Mathematics and Biology in History</b><br /><br />When we isolate people in a specific region, such as Mesoamerica (O), we are not diminishing their humanity nor making them superior to other groups. Biologically, they remain the same as other <i>Homo sapiens</i> (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('82544083-aaad-4760-963b-f433bd3e8729'); return false;\"><i>History Tracers Team</i></a>). This separation is simply a method used to study groups with common cultural characteristics.<br /><br />Therefore, when we move beyond studying isolated events from each cradle of civilization and focus solely on human DNA, these cultural divisions disappear. We can then visualize humanity as a unified whole, connected since the dawn of species evolution. This connection can be represented mathematically by the union (&cup;):<br /><br />H = A &cup; M &cup; O &cup; E &cup; C &cup; I &cup; h<br /><br />The result of this operation leads us to a common origin point, around 250,000 years ago (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('dd34414b-8f55-4e5e-877a-c0e111e871be'); return false;\">Wang, Richard J., <i>et al.</i></a> ; <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('eda6e242-751a-46b3-b5f7-0c4489d9b374'); return false;\"><i>History Tracers Team</i></a>). During this time, there were no cultural differences or distinct regions; there was only the species <i>Homo sapiens</i>. This idea of unity is illustrated in Figure 7, symbolizing humanity without divisions, founded on mutual respect and shared genetic connections.</div></div></center></p>",
                      "<p class=\"desc\"><svg fill=\"none\" stroke=\"black\"><circle cx=\"145\" cy=\"75\" r=\"70\"></circle> <text x=\"140\" y=\"80\" font-size=\"2em\">H</text> </svg></p>",
                      "<p class=\"desc\">Figure 7: Representation of humanity as a whole, without divisions, based on mutual respect and shared genetic information.</p>"
                    ]
                }
            ]
